-- Sub-Saharan African Stocks: Eaagads, Finbank, Naiade, Oceanic, Zenith Move
-- B y   E r i c   O m b o k   a n d   V i n c e n t   N w a n m a
-- 2010-10-29T15:15:22Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-29/sub-saharan-african-stocks-eaagads-finbank-naiade-oceanic-zenith-move.html
Kenya’s  All-Share Index  surged the
most since Aug. 3, climbing 2.1 percent to close at 84.12 by 3
p.m. in Nairobi. The gauge has increased 2.1 percent this month.  Mauritius’s  SEMDEX Index  rose for a sixth day, adding 0.5
percent to 1,861.76 by the 1:30 p.m. close in Port Louis. The
measure rallied 5.7 percent in October, a fifth consecutive
monthly gain.  The  Ghana Stock Exchange All-Share Index  advanced 1.1
percent to 6,895.25 by the 1 p.m. close in Accra. The index has
gained 0.9 percent this month, a third of advances.  Namibia’s  FTSE/Namibia Overall Index  added 0.2 percent to
close at 826.69 by 5 p.m. in Windhoek, extending its gain this
month to 3.1 percent.  The  Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index  retreated for
the first time in three days, dropping 0.1 percent to 25,042.08
by the 1 p.m. close in Lagos, according to the exchange’s
 website . The measure has surged 8.6 percent this month, the
biggest monthly increase since May 2009, according to data
compiled by Bloomberg.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding South Africa. Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Eaagads Ltd.  (EGCL KN), a Kenyan coffee producer, added
3.75 shillings, or 7.5 percent, to 53.5 shillings, the highest
since Sept. 9. Part of the company’s land would be used for the
$5 billion Tatu City residential complex outside Nairobi, the
capital, Business Daily reported, citing Patrick Mweheire, the
chief executive officer of Renaissance Group’s Kenyan unit.  The Russian investment group bought a 62 percent stake in
Eaagads in December last year, acquiring 300 acres (121
hectares) of Eaagads’ Tatu coffee estate to develop Tatu City,
the Nairobi-based newspaper cited Mweheire as saying.  Finbank Plc  (FIRSTINL NL), a Nigerian lender bailed out by
the country’s central bank last year, advanced to the highest
since April, climbing 3 kobo, or 4.8 percent, to 66 kobo. The
company said it was in talks with potential investors that may
lead to its recapitalization, according to a statement published
in the Lagos-based Guardian newspaper today. Reuters reported
 First City Monument Bank Plc  (FCMB NL) made a bid to buy
Finbank, citing an official at FCMB that it didn’t identify.  FCMB rallied the most in four months, adding 33 kobo, or 5
percent, to 6.95 naira.  Kenya Airways Ltd.  (KNAL KN) climbed the most in almost two
weeks, increasing 1 shillings, or 2.3 percent, to 44.75
shillings after saying it carried 9 percent more passengers in
the fiscal second quarter compared with a year earlier.  Passengers flown by sub-Saharan Africa’s third-biggest
airline totaled 849,566 in the three months through September,
the Nairobi-based airline said in an e-mailed statement
yesterday.  Naiade Resorts Ltd.  (NRL MP), a Mauritian hotel operator,
rose the most since Oct. 5, adding 1 rupee, or 3.5 percent, to
30 rupees. Shareholders approved a rights offer of 27.8 million
shares at 18 rupees each and the sale of 50 million units of
convertible bonds at 10 rupees each, the company said in a
statement to the stock exchange today.  Oceanic Bank International Plc  (OCEANIC NL), a Nigerian
lender bailed out by the country’s central bank last year,
gained for a 15th day, the longest streak of gains since Jan.
14, adding 11 kobo, or the maximum daily limit of 5 percent, to
2.31 naira.  The company reported a return to profit for the nine months
through September, with net income totaling 10.4 billion naira
($69.3 million) from a loss of 64.4 billion naira a year
earlier, the company said in a statement e-mailed by the Lagos-
based Nigerian Stock Exchange today.  Unilever Ghana Ltd.  (UNIL GN), a household-goods maker,
increased for the first time since Oct. 21, adding 7 pesewas, or
1.3 percent, to 5.52 cedis. The company appointed David Mureithi
as managing director, replacing  Charles Cofie , Myjoyonline
reported, citing a statement signed by Sampson Dontoh, human
resource director of the company.  Union Bank of Nigeria Plc  (UBN NL), a Nigerian lender
bailed out by the nation’s central bank last year, rose to the
highest since Oct. 25, adding 16 kobo, or 4.1 percent, to 4.09
naira. The company has shortlisted two potential investors and
is in negotiations with one of them according to Francis Barde,
head of corporate affairs at the bank, who spoke in a phone
interview today in Lagos.  Zenith Bank Plc  (ZENITHBA NL), Nigeria’s biggest lender by
market value, fell the most since Oct. 6, slipping 43 kobo, or
3.2 percent, to 13.17 naira. The company had its recommendation
lowered to “accumulate” from “buy” at African Alliance
Securities Ltd.  To contact the reporters on this story:
